# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dora-metrics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:dora-metrics/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:dora-metrics/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Technology-driven teams need ways to measure performance so that they can assess how they’re doing today, prioritize improvements, and validate their progress.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] DORA has identified five software delivery performance metrics that provide an effective way of measuring the outcomes of the software delivery process.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] DORA’s research shows that these performance metrics predict better organizational performance and well-being for team members.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] These metrics have evolved alongside the technology landscape: shifting from the original four keys to the current five-metric model.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] These software delivery performance metrics can be viewed as both leading and lagging indicators.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Leading indicators typically signal potential future changes in a system while lagging indicators reflect past performance and outcomes.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] DORA’s software delivery performance metrics focus on a team’s ability to deliver software safely, quickly, and efficiently.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] They can be divided into metrics that show the throughput of software changes, and metrics that show instability of software changes.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Throughput is a measure of how many changes can move through the system over a period of time.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Higher throughput means that the system can move more changes through to the production environment.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Instability is a measure of how well the software deployments go.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] When deployments go well, teams can confidently push more changes into production and users are less likely to experience issues with the application immediately following a deployment.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Taken together, these two factors for software delivery performance (throughput and instability) give teams a high-level understanding of their software delivery performance.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Measuring these over time provides insight into how software delivery performance is changing.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] These factors can be used to measure any application or service, regardless of the technology stack, the complexity of the deployment processes, or its end users.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] DORA’s research has repeatedly demonstrated that speed and stability are not tradeoffs.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] In fact, we see that the metrics are correlated for most teams.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Top performers do well across all five metrics, and low performers do poorly.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] These metrics work for any type of technology your organization is delivering, but are best suited for measuring one application or service at a time.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Whether you are building large language models, retail banking applications, mobile food ordering applications, or mainframe-based travel systems, these five metrics can help you assess the delivery performance of your application.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Apply the metrics in the context of the application or service your team is delivering.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] The context for your application, organization, and users will vary from other applications that your organization is delivering.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] While it may be tempting to blend metrics across multiple teams–or entire organizations–these differences in context mean that doing so can be problematic.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Share your own cautionary tales with the DORA community by posting to the mailing list at https://dora.community.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] DORA’s research goes beyond these five metrics, exploring various capabilities that contribute to high performance.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] You can learn more about these capabilities and their impact on software delivery by visiting the capability catalog.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] By understanding and effectively utilizing DORA metrics, you can gain valuable insights into your software delivery performance and drive continuous improvement.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Remember, the goal is to deliver better software faster, and DORA metrics provide the compass to orient teams toward that objective.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] A common approach to improving the five key metrics discussed in this guide is reducing the batch size of changes for an application.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Smaller changes are easier to rationalize and to move through the delivery process.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Smaller changes are also easier to recover from if there’s a failure.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Teams should make each change as small as possible to make the delivery process fast and stable.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Working in this way contributes to both change throughput and change stability.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] We have found that an effective way of making changes is to gather the cross-functional team that is responsible for prioritizing, building, delivering, and operating an application for a discussion about improving their software delivery performance.
[src:dora-metrics/dora-metrics-four-keys] Join us in the DORA Community for ongoing discussions about how to implement DORA metrics in your organization!
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] A **lead time** is the latency between the initiation and completion of a process.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] For example, the lead time between the placement of an order and delivery of new cars by a given manufacturer might be between two weeks and six months, depending on various particularities.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] One business dictionary defines "manufacturing lead time" as the total time required to manufacture an item, including order preparation time, queue time, setup time, run time, move time, inspection time, and put-away time.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] For make-to-order products, it is the time between release of an order and the production and shipment that fulfill that order.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] For make-to-stock products, it is the time taken from the release of an order to production and receipt into finished goods inventory.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] A conventional definition of lead time in a supply chain management context is the time from the moment the customer places an order (the moment the supplier learns of the requirement) to the moment it is ready for delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] In the absence of finished goods or intermediate (work in progress) inventory, it is the time it takes to actually manufacture the order without any inventory other than raw materials.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The lead time applicable to material flows within a supply chain may be paralleled by the concept of "information lead time".
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Mason-Jones and Towill report that reductions in both material flow lead time and information lead time are necessary to secure supply chain performance improvements.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Several writers have referred to the importance of "information enriched supply chains" in this context.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] In the manufacturing environment, lead time has the same definition as that used in supply chain management, but it includes the time required to ship the parts from the supplier.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Shipping time is included because the manufacturing company needs to know when the parts will be available for material requirements planning purposes.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] It is also possible to include within lead time the time it takes for a company to process and have the part ready for manufacturing once it has been received.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The time it takes a company to unload a product from a truck, inspect it, and move it into storage ("put-away time") is not trivial.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] With tight manufacturing constraints or when a company is using Just In Time manufacturing, it is important for supply chain to know how long their own internal processes take.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] For example, Company A needs a part that can be manufactured in two days once Company B has received an order.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] It takes three days for company A to receive the part once shipped, and one additional day before the part is ready to go into manufacturing.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] To best meet the customer needs, a company should work towards the shortest possible lead time in manufacturing, production, and delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] When talking about Order Lead Time (OLT) it is important to differentiate between the definitions that may exist around this concept.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Although they look similar, there are differences between them that help the industry to model the order behavior of their customers.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The OLTRequested will be determined by the difference between the date the customer wants the material in his facilities (wish date) and the date when they provided its order to the supplier.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The OLTQuote will be determined by the difference between the date the customer agree to receive the material in their facilities (Quote date) and the date when the order is provided to the supplier.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The OLTActual will be determined by the difference between the day the provider deliver the material (Delivery date) and the date when they enter the order in the system.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The OLTConfirmed will be determined by the difference between the date the confirmed date by the provider to deliver the material in the customer facilities (Confirmed date) and the date when they provide the order to the supplier.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The volume metric could be applied to the 4 types of OLT.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The figure obtained from this calculation will be the average time (e.g. in days) between order placing and the requested delivery date of a specific customer under consideration of the average quantities ordered during that particular time.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] In project management, lead time is the time it takes to complete a task or a set of interdependent tasks.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The lead of the entire project would be the overall duration of the critical path for the project.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] According to the PMBOK (7th edition) by the Project Management Institute (PMI), lead time is the "time between a customer request and the actual delivery." The lead time is a deliverable metric and a customary measure.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] The lead time shows the amount of elapsed time from a chunk of work or story entering the backlog, to the end of the iteration or release.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] A smaller lead time means that the process is more effective and the project team is more productive.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Lead time is also the saved time by starting an activity before its predecessor is completed.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] According to the PMBOK (7th edition) by PMI, lead is "The amount of time whereby a successor activity can be advanced with respect to a predecessor activity".
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] An example would be scheduling the start of a two-week activity dependent with the finish of the successor activity with a lead of two weeks so they will finish at the same time.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Lead time in publishing describes the amount of time that a journalist has between receiving a writing assignment and submitting the completed piece.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] This is the production period of a particular publication before releasing it to the public as the issue date.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Depending on the publication, lead times can be anything from a couple of hours to many months/years.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Lead time (when referring to a disease) is the length of time between detection of a disease through screening and the moment in time where it would have normally presented with symptoms and led to a diagnosis.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] An example of this is seen with breast cancer population screening, where women who are asymptomatic have a positive test result with mammography, whereas the underlying disease would have taken many more years to manifest.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Lead time in video games can refer to the amount of time certain special, important actions in high-twitch action games, such as using health-recovering items, may need to take in order to be completed successfully.
[src:dora-metrics/lead-time] Lead time can be used to prevent players from abusing helpful abilities or items by making them a little more difficult to use safely, requiring some strategy, risk or caution.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A **performance indicator** or **key performance indicator** (**KPI**) is a type of performance measurement used to evaluate the success of an organization, activity, project, or process in achieving defined objectives.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] KPIs provide a focus for strategic and operational improvement, support evidence-based decision-making, and help organizations identify and monitor factors critical to performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] KPIs may measure progress toward operational targets such as quality levels, efficiency, or customer satisfaction or toward broader strategic goals.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The selection of appropriate KPIs depends on an organization’s priorities and context, and indicators often differ across functional areas such as finance, sales, operations, or human resources.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Management frameworks such as the **balanced scorecard** are commonly used to structure KPI selection and align measurement with strategy.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Performance indicators are applied across sectors including business, government, healthcare, and technical systems.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Their effectiveness depends on clear definition, reliable data, and appropriate interpretation, as poorly designed indicators may create unintended incentives or fail to capture meaningful outcomes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] KPIs are used not only for business organizations but also for technical aspects such as machine performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] For example, a machine used for production in a factory would output various signals indicating how the current machine status is (e.g., machine sensor signals).
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Some signals or signals as a result of processing the existing signals may represent the high-level machine performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] These representative signals can be KPI for the machine.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The effective use of performance indicators requires a clear understanding of their different types and purposes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Indicators can be categorised along several key dimensions to ensure a balanced and comprehensive measurement system that supports strategic objectives.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A well-designed set of indicators will draw from multiple categories to avoid unintended consequences and provide a holistic view of organisational performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A primary method of categorisation is based on the **dimension of performance** being measured.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The Balanced Scorecard framework, for instance, groups indicators into four perspectives: financial (e.g., profitability), customer (e.g., satisfaction), internal business processes (e.g., efficiency), and learning and growth (e.g., innovation).
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] This approach prevents over-reliance on financial metrics alone.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Indicators are also commonly distinguished by their **time orientation and function**.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Another critical distinction is based on the **nature of the data**.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Quantitative indicators provide objective, numerical measurement (e.g., unit output, error rates), while qualitative indicators capture subjective, often perceptual data (e.g., stakeholder satisfaction, brand reputation) typically gathered through surveys and interviews.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Furthermore, indicators can be designed for different **levels of the organisation**.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Strategic indicators monitor progress toward top-level goals, operational indicators track departmental or process efficiency, and individual indicators align personal objectives with organisational priorities.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Selecting the right mix of categories is a strategic exercise.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] An overemphasis on lagging quantitative indicators can lead to short-termism and "gaming" of metrics, while focusing solely on leading or qualitative indicators may lack a connection to ultimate outcomes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A balanced portfolio of indicators across these categories is therefore essential for effective performance management.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The first step in performance measurement is determining what to measure.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Performance indictors may be applied at various stages within a programme, service, or organisational process.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] These points capture distinct dimensions of performance, ranging from the earliest stages of resource allocation to final outcomes achieved.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Mapping indicators across this continuum helps ensure measurement provides a clear picture of performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The points of measurement may also relate to the relationship between inputs and outputs (productivity), and outputs and outcome (effectiveness).
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Control (the extent to which employees can influence a result) and mechanism (the causal link between employees’ effort and a performance dimension) further shape measurement decisions.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Selecting the appropriate point of measurement is not simply a technical choice but also a strategic one.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] For example, focusing narrowly on inputs or outputs can incentivise ‘box-ticking’ behaviours and obscure whether real value is being created.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Conversely, outcome and impact indicators may be harder to attribute to organisational effort, especially in complex public sector environments.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A balanced approach can involve linking indicators across multiple points of measurement, to trace the relationships between resources, activities and ultimate value.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] However, this requires careful design to avoid measurement burdens and to ensure alignment with an organisation’s overall strategic objectives.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Quality assurance across the points of measurement helps ensure indicators not only track activity levels but also produce robust, consistent and credible performance data.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Once appropriate points of measurement have been determined, the next task is to identify specific indicators that meaningfully capture performance at that stage.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] An indicator is a measurable variable used to show whether progress is being made towards a goal, rather than the goal itself.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Choice of indicators reflects managerial decisions about what counts as successful performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Indicators may be financial, such as revenue growth, or non-financial, such as customer satisfaction rates.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A good indicator should be simple to understand while aligning closely with business or organisational goals.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The process of identifying indicators is often guided by frameworks such as SMART (specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, time-bound).
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Alternatives like the FABRIC principles emphasise ideal performance information is focused, appropriate, balanced, robust, integrated, and cost-effective.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In the public sector, where outcomes may depend on many different organisations and external influences, careful selection is needed to avoid misleading or overly broad results.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Beyond the technical steps, several broader considerations shape indicator usefulness.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Indicators must be simple enough for managers and other stakeholders, including shareholders or the public, to understand but precise enough to capture what matters.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Over-simplified indicators may distort or fail to drive performance, while overly complex or too numerous indicators may fail to gain traction.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In the public sector, multiple organisations may influence outcomes indicators, and may sometimes develop a shared outcomes framework with reporting to show the particular role an individual organisation.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Where a clear link exists between employee effort and performance, indicators may be connected to motivation, reward and appraisal systems.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Data quality is another important consideration.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Indicators depend on reliable and consistent information.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Weak systems can undermine credibility, shaping which indicators are ultimately preferred.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Finally, given the risks of gaming, data fabrication, and selective reporting on indictors, organisations should consider verifiability of underlying data when selecting indicators and choose indicators that are not susceptible to manipulation.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Many of these customer KPIs are developed and managed with customer relationship management software.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Faster availability of data is a competitive issue for most organizations.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] For example, businesses that have higher operational/credit risk (involving for example credit cards or wealth management) may want weekly or even daily availability of KPI analysis, facilitated by appropriate IT systems and tools.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) is a set of broadly accepted nonfinancial metrics that reflect manufacturing success.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Most professional services firms (for example, management consultancies, systems integration firms, or digital marketing agencies) use three key performance indicators to track the health of their businesses.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] They typically use professional services automation (PSA) software to keep track of and manage these metrics.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Businesses can utilize supply chain KPIs to establish and monitor progress toward a variety of goals, including lean manufacturing objectives, minority business enterprise and diversity spending, environmental "green" initiatives, cost avoidance programs and low-cost country sourcing targets.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Suppliers can implement KPIs to gain a competitive advantage.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Suppliers have instant access to a user-friendly portal for submitting standardized cost savings templates.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Suppliers and their customers exchange vital supply chain performance data while gaining visibility to the exact status of cost improvement projects and cost savings documentation.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In a warehouse, the manager will use KPIs that target best use of the facility, like the receiving and put away KPIs to measure the receiving efficiency and the putaway cost per line.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Storage KPIs can also be used to determine the efficiency of the storage space and the carrying cost of the inventory.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Governments around the world have adopted performance indicators as part of broader performance management reforms.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] These initiatives emerged from general concerns about performance deficits in the public sector, and the belief that systematic measurement could improve accountability and outcomes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] While governments have established extensive systems for collecting performance data, research suggests that the value of these indicators depends on whether managers effectively use the information in their decision-making processes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Factors influencing the use of performance data include individual values, leadership roles, organisational culture, and external pressures.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Managers with strong public service motivation are more likely to engage with performance information because they see it as a means of achieving public goals.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Task-specific leaders often use indicators more actively than generalist leaders who face broader political responsibilities.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Organisational cultures that emphasise learning, flexibility, and innovation are more likely to foster the use of performance information, whereas rigid or highly centralised environments may discourage it.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Citizen participation can also create demand for greater accountability, encouraging managers to apply performance data to justify decisions and demonstrate transparency.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] International examples show the diversity of approaches.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The provincial government of Ontario, Canada has used performance indicators since the late 1990s to assess higher education institutions, reporting on measures such as graduate satisfaction, employment rates, and student outcomes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In England, Public Health England applies indicators to monitor national health screening programmes, while UK government departments publish key contract-related indicators to improve service transparency.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The United States requires federal agencies to set strategic goals and report on progress under the Government Performance and Results Act.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The New Zealand Treasury’s Living Standards Framework and associated wellbeing indicators provide a broader set of measures that move beyond economic performance to social and environmental outcomes.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Although performance indicators are now widespread, their effectiveness remains debated.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] It can be argued that indicators oversimplify complex goals, encourage symbolic compliance, and shift attention to what is easily measurable rather than what is substantively important.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] On the other hand, when well-designed and used within supportive cultures, indicators can strengthen accountability, guide learning, and improve service delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Performance indicators are widely used in human resource management (HRM) to assess recruitment, retention, performance, and employee well-being.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In the public sector, these measures are shaped by distinctive institutional constraints and workforce motivations.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Common HRM indicators include employee turnover rates, time to fill vacancies, absenteeism, staff satisfaction, and survey results.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] The effectiveness of HRM practices has been examined across public, semi-public, and private organisations.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A large meta-analysis using the ability-motivation-opportunity (AMO) framework found that HRM practices positively influence individual performance in all sectors, but with sector-specific variations.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Ability-enhancing practices such as training and selective recruitment are consistently associated with higher job satisfaction and performance.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Motivation-enhancing practices, such as performance-based pay, show weaker impacts in public organisations, where employees are often driven more by intrinsic and altruistic motivations than extrinsic rewards.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Opportunity-enhancing practices, such as participatory decision-making and job autonomy, appear particularly important in encouraging extra-role behaviours like collaboration and knowledge-sharing.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Employee turnover is a critical indicator for HRM.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] While traditionally seen as negative, research suggests that turnover may have more complex effects.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A study of several hundred public school districts in Texas over nine years found that turnover was linearly negative for basic educational outcomes, such as standardised test scores, but showed a non-linear “inverted U-shaped” relationship with more complex outcomes like college readiness.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] This indicates that low to moderate turnover may introduce new skills and perspectives, benefiting organisational performance, while very high turnover imposes significant costs and reduces effectiveness.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Other HRM indicators reflect absenteeism, which is often monitored as a proxy for workforce wellbeing and organisational health.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Staff satisfaction surveys are also commonly used to measure morale, commitment, and engagement, though their interpretation may be shaped by broader organisational culture and leadership practices.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Performance Indicators (PIs) are widely used to measure, manage and provide public accountability across sectors like healthcare, business, education and government.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] However, they can have challenges and limitations that may affect data accuracy, relevance, and effectiveness if not carefully considered.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In practice, overseeing key performance indicators can prove expensive or difficult for organizations.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Some indicators such as staff morale may be impossible to quantify.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] As such, dubious KPIs can be adopted that can be used as a rough guide rather than a precise benchmark.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Key performance indicators can also lead to perverse incentives and unintended consequences as a result of employees working to the specific measurements at the expense of the actual quality or value of their work.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Sometimes, collecting statistics can become a substitute for a better understanding of the problems, so the use of dubious KPIs can result in progress in aims and measured effectiveness becoming different.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] For example, during the Vietnam War, US soldiers were shown to be effective in kill ratios and high body counts, but this was misleading when used to measure aims as it did not show the lack of progress towards the US goal of increasing South Vietnamese government control of its territory.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Another example would be to measure the productivity of a software development team in terms of lines of source code written.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] This approach can easily add large amounts of dubious code, thereby inflating the line count but adding little value in terms of systemic improvement.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] A similar problem arises when a footballer kicks a ball uselessly to build up their statistics.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Strategies to address and mitigate problems with PIs requires a thoughtful, systemic approach.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Further examples may include in nursing, replacing rigid throughput metrics with indicators that reflect quality of care, and patient experience.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] In education, balance test scores with indicators of student engagement and learning environment quality.
[src:dora-metrics/performance-indicator] Finally, in public services, include metrics for community impact and equity alongside traditional efficiency indicators.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:dora-metrics/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] In software engineering and development, a **software metric** is a standard of measure of a degree to which a software system or process possesses some property.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Even if a metric is not a measurement (metrics are functions, while measurements are the numbers obtained by the application of metrics), often the two terms are used as synonyms.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Since quantitative measurements are essential in all sciences, there is a continuous effort by computer science practitioners and theoreticians to bring similar approaches to software development.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] The goal is obtaining objective, reproducible and quantifiable measurements, which may have numerous valuable applications in schedule and budget planning, cost estimation, quality assurance, testing, software debugging, software performance optimization, and optimal personnel task assignments.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Another source of difficulty and debate is in determining which metrics matter, and what they mean.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Researchers argue that commonly used software metrics, promoted frequently in academic research, are not practically useful for software professionals' decision-making.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] A specific measurement may target one or more of the above aspects, or the balance between them, for example as an indicator of team motivation or project performance.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Additionally metrics vary between static and dynamic program code, as well as for object oriented software (systems).
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Some software development practitioners point out that simplistic measurements can cause more harm than good.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Others have noted that metrics have become an integral part of the software development process.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Impact of measurement on programmer psychology have raised concerns for harmful effects to performance due to stress, performance anxiety, and attempts to cheat the metrics, while others find it to have positive impact on developers value towards their own work, and prevent them being undervalued.
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Some argue that the definition of many measurement methodologies are imprecise, and consequently it is often unclear how tools for computing them arrive at a particular result, while others argue that imperfect quantification is better than none (“You can’t control what you can't measure.”).
[src:dora-metrics/software-metric] Evidence shows that software metrics are being widely used by government agencies, the US military, NASA, IT consultants, academic institutions, and commercial and academic development estimation software.
